If you're caught with two pounds of pot that you plan to sell, plan on going
to jail for up to seven years.

With 500 pounds, you can kiss your freedom completely goodbye.

But head down to Southern Arizona, near the border, do the exact same thing,
and in many cases you get off scott-free.

No prosecution, no penalty, no prison...in fact - not even a slap on the
hand.

County prosecutors say it's enormously frustrating and for the drug cartels,
enormously profitable.

But this sweet deal only applies if you're illegal and smuggling 500-pounds
or less.

And therein lies one of our country's dirty little secrets: Mexican drug
runners getting a free pass back to Mexico if they're caught with less than
a quarter-ton of pot.

Cochise County attorney Ed Rheinheimer spells it out. &quot;If a seizure is made
of an amount less than 500 pounds, the case doesn't get prosecuted.&quot;

You read that right.

Drug runners doing business without punishment.

But don't blame the county attorneys.

Remember: These are federal cases and should be federally prosecuted.

But guess what?

They don't get prosecuted by the feds and now, they don't get prosecuted by
guys like Ed Rheinheimer, either.

&quot;Since 2003 we stopped prosecuting federal referrals because of a lack of
resources.&quot;

Until 2003 Rheinheimer's office handled about 150-of these federal cases a
year.

Quantities of pot annually with a street value as high as 60-million bucks.

But his county, like others, didn't have the money, prosecutors, jail space
or court-appointed attorneys to keep up with a federal referral literally
every other day.

&quot;When the marijuana ends up in a middle school in Lincoln, Nebraska, the
parents of the kids who get a hold of that marijuana have no idea that the
reason that stuff ended up in Nebraska was because the federal government is
not prosecuting the stuff on the border and allowing the stuff to get
through,&quot; says Rheinheimer.

And while these &quot;weight limits&quot; are unfamiliar to most Americans - drug
cartels know them well and plan accordingly.

Sergeant Terry Parish warehouses the seizures.  We walked through store
rooms holding marijuana from floor to ceiling.

Lisa Fletcher: &quot;How many of these guys do you think are aware of this sort
of unspoken rule that if you've got less than 500 pounds, you're probably
not going to get prosecuted?&quot;

&quot;I think probably more of them are aware of it than individual officers
are.  Their intelligence is very good, it's what they do for a living.&quot;

And they do it every night...all along Arizona's border.

We spent two nights down there with deputies and border patrol and watched
as drug runners tried to race through.  One group we chased ended up dumping
their load to try to get away.  Not that it would have mattered. We were in
Santa Cruz county - another border county that can't afford to handle the
criminals the feds won't take.

Sergeant Parish told us the thinks it's almost criminal.  &quot;As a law
enforcement officer it makes me feel terrible.  As a citizen of this country
it makes me feel terrible.&quot;

It's hard to know how many drug runners are getting a free bus ride back to
Mexico because no one seems to keep track.

We went looking for answers to the office of Dan Knauss - the US Attorney
for Arizona.

Lisa Fletcher: &quot;You are the top dog for federal prosecution in this state.
How do you justify to Arizona citizens that you are blowing-off these 400,
